[...]Document continued, lots of previous truths on page, then a heading[...]

 Issues Identified to Date

 1.  The primary issue is that the integration as written assumed that all
 locations for a MID would always be settled by a single processor.
     We found merchants boarded on CardConnect who have multiple locations
 settling to different processors.
 When performing reconciliation, this causes duplicate transactions,
 because it is not possible to tie a given transaction to a specific
 location for settlement.
 There are also VAR sheet implications, where fees by location ID are not
 possible.

	 [...] several redacted lines [...]

 The gateway
 does not store the location ID on the settlement record that results from
 a transaction so there is no ability to reconcile this.

 2.  There are also VAR sheet implications to this. The two biggest being
 how do credit/debit % fees work across MIDs then get split to locations,

	 [...] redacted lines [...]

 will locations for a MID on occasion receive the same transactions across
 multiple acquirers for settlement?

 3.  [...]This item is fully redacted[...]

 4.  The CardConnect gateway does not support auto-close.
     This means batches will remain open until manually settled, so d+1
 funding will not be possible.

 5.  [...]This item is fully redacted[...]

 6.   The CardConnect gateway is not designed to handle a large number of MIDs
 being added concurrently during boarding (i.e. more than 500).
     It is expected that this will cause timeout issues.

 7.  The CardConnect gateway uses different Bank IDs for debit and credit
     transactions through the same processor.
     This prevents us from being able to consolidate settlement deposits to
 merchants boarded by CardConnect.

 8.  The CardConnect retrieval system is not designed to handle the expected
 volume of transactions.
     It is expected that this will impact our ability to satisfy retrieval
 requests in a timely fashion.
